  "prompt": "Strep b when pregnant?",
  "response": "Group B Streptococcus (GBS) is a common bacteria that can be present in the vagina or rectum of pregnant women. Here are key points about GBS during pregnancy:\n\n1. Screening\n- Typically tested between 35-37 weeks of pregnancy\n- Simple swab test of vagina and rectum\n\n2. Potential Risks\n- Can potentially cause serious infection in newborns\n- May lead to sepsis, pneumonia, or meningitis in babies\n\n3. Treatment\n- Antibiotics during labor for GBS-positive women\n- Usually intravenous penicillin\n- Reduces risk of transmission to baby\n\n4. Risk Factors\n- Previous baby with GBS infection\n- Urinary tract infection with GBS\n- Fever during labor\n- Premature delivery\n\n5. Prevention\n- Routine screening\n- Antibiotic treatment during labor\n- Good prenatal care\n\n6. Important Notes\n- Most babies born to GBS-positive mothers remain healthy\n- About 1 in 4 pregnant women carry GBS\n- Treatment significantly reduces infant infection risk\n\nAlways consult with your healthcare provider for personalized advice and guidance.",
